---
import Layout from "@/layouts/main.astro";

const title = "Flick Trainer & Visual Tracking Science | CogniArena";
const description = "Understand smooth pursuit eye movements, motion coherence thresholds, and predictive saccade mechanisms for visual tracking performance.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://cogniarena.com/learn/flick-trainer";

const schemaJson = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Science of Visual Tracking and Flick Response Training",
  "description": "Examine smooth pursuit gain, motion coherence detection limits, and the predictive saccade system in dynamic target tracking.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Dr. Alan Vanc",
    "jobTitle": "Neuroscience Researcher"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "CogniArena"
  }
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonicalUrl={canonicalUrl} schemaJson={schemaJson}>
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 w-full max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-3">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">
        <span>Learning Center</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>Pillar Page</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground animate-fade-in">
        Flick Trainer & Visual Tracking Science
      </h1>
      <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        A scientific breakdown of smooth pursuit, motion coherence perception, and the prediction mechanisms underlying rapid flick responses.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="flex flex-col gap-10 border-t border-card-border pt-10">
      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">1. Smooth Pursuit Eye Movements</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Smooth pursuit is the eye movement system that maintains foveal fixation on a moving target, with velocity ranges from 1 to 30 degrees per second. The pursuit system operates with a latency of approximately 100ms and uses retinal slip velocity signals from the middle temporal visual area to compute corrective eye acceleration. Pursuit gain, the ratio of eye velocity to target velocity, typically ranges from 0.9 to 1.0 for predictable trajectories but drops sharply for sudden directional changes.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">2. Motion Coherence Thresholds</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Motion coherence refers to the percentage of dots or visual elements moving in a common direction among random noise. The human visual system can detect coherent motion with as few as 5% to 10% of elements moving together, a threshold mediated by area MT/V5. This sensitivity allows the brain to segment moving targets from cluttered backgrounds, but it comes with a temporal integration window of 200ms to 400ms, meaning brief flick events near the coherence threshold require extended processing before a response can be generated.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">3. Predictive Saccades and Anticipatory Control</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The brain does not wait for visual feedback alone; it builds internal forward models that predict target motion trajectories. The cerebellum, particularly the dorsal vermis and flocculus, generates predictive corrections that anticipate target position 80ms to 150ms into the future. When a target disappears or flickers, these predictive mechanisms sustain the pursuit trajectory for up to 300ms before the system reverts to catch-up saccades.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">What is smooth pursuit in visual tracking?</h4>
            <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">Smooth pursuit is a voluntary eye movement that matches eye velocity to a moving target's velocity, keeping the image stable on the fovea. It operates differently from saccades and requires a visible moving stimulus.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">Can visual tracking speed be improved with training?</h4>
            <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">Yes. Repeated exposure to predictable motion trajectories improves pursuit gain and reduces phase lag through cerebellar adaptation. Training also enhances the precision of predictive saccade timing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <p class="text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed text-center border-t border-card-border pt-10">
      Test your visual tracking ability on the <a href="/tests/flick-trainer" class="text-accent underline underline-offset-2 hover:brightness-110 transition-all">Flick Trainer</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
